snippet.textDisplay:
Statement by President of Serbia:   "..Dear citizens of Serbia, we are faced with many problems and pressures in the region and from all over the world, but what they have never managed to take away from us as a nation, is our heart, pride and dignity. I say this because of everything that is happening in Melbourne, Australia, and not because I am interested in getting any political points, because I have never adorned myself with other people's feathers, but because of attacks on Novak Djokovic, a Serbian citizen, a Serb, a citizen of this country, and for reasons unknown to us. This has reached such proportions that it is impossible for me not to speak out and say not only what I think, but also what our response to Australia is. I probably would not have said a word after the repeated decision of the Australian authorities to cancel the visa for Novak Djokovic, if the Prime Minister of Australia Scott Morrison hadn’t spoken and said that he was satisfied and welcomed the decision to cancel the visa of the world's best tennis player.
- I am amazed primarily by the fact that such decisions are made by the executive authorities, and after valid decisions of the judicial authorities. They often preach to us about what rule of law should be. Can you imagine what it would look like if a minister in Serbia could annul a decisions of judges?! But by doing that, they actually showed us what an irrelevant justice sector looks like as full power seems to be in the hands of executive authorities. But let me go back to an even more important issue, and that is the matter of morals. If you wanted to prevent Novak from winning the trophy in Melbourne for the 10th time, why didn't you deport him immediately, why didn't you tell him that it was not possible for him to enter your country, why are you maltreating him, and not only him but his family? And a whole nation, a free and proud nation. Is that what you need in order to win some elections, or to please your public? Well, here’s a president from a small country who has the guts to say all this to a great prime minister of a large country. You know why I can do that? Because I'm telling the truth and because you know I'm telling the truth. We will fight for Novak Djokovic, and the fact that you will harass him for a day, two or five, will not change the opinion of our people about the people of Australia, whom we look upon with high regard, nor will we change our opinion about Novak Djokovic.
You can write hundreds and thousands of texts of the worst possible nature about him, but he will remain the best tennis player of all time and will always be in our hearts. And you, who think you will achieve something by harassing him, will never live up to Novak Djokovic, and not only him but any ordinary person, a member of either your or our proud nation. Serbia will stand by Novak Djokovic and Serbia will always know how to respond to you, by behaving much better than you have treated Novak Djokovic and by respecting everything that is expected of an adequate representation of one’s country. Long live Serbia! Novak, we're with you!.."
